pic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: starting out</span><hr size=1> yes yes yes.....but which should i learn first.........................................the language itself, or the writing? or both at once? <br>i know a guy who knows a guy who non stop studied japanese and learned the entire language and writing in 1 year! its true too...he's super smart  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=superflat>superflat</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/14/02 11:48:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=649.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: starting out</span><hr size=1> Look, it doesn't really matter which you learn first: it should only take about a week to learn each one anyway so its not a big deal.  The way I see it though, you should do hiragana first, then katakana.  You need hiragana to actually compose sentences, and presumably you are studying grammar too.  Katakana is not at all necessary for basic sentences (outside of stating your name), so if you have to put one off, that's it.  And yes you should study the language too.  Just knowing how to write the letters is pretty close to useless. <br><br>As for your your story... well I don't believe much that is told to me by someone on the internet about a guy who knows a guy.  If you mean by &quot;learning the entire language&quot; that he became fluent, I'd say that its bullsh!t.  Even if he were a genius, that's just not going to happen unless he spent some time abroad, much less in a year's time.  But whatever, its really doesn't matter.  Good luck. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uunangbangkay.showPublicProfile?language=EN>UnangBangkay</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/15/02 12:23:17 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=649.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> From one beginner to another..</span><hr size=1> Here's what I do (I study alone, from a book, so it isn't the best):<br><br>I would suggest starting with speaking, combined with practice in Katakana first, then Hiragana. Why Katakana? Writing english words in it helps make it easier to get the hang of the way the Japanese pronounce, and thus write. That, and you can use it right away, by learning to impress your friends. Hiragana comes next.<br><br>If you're an anime or manga fan, watching subtitled anime regularly helps a lot with general understanding, since you can locate specific words once you get the hang of the &quot;A wa B desu&quot; sentence structure. Music isn't the very best way to get the hang of speaking conversationally, because words and pronunciations are often too rapid or cut to give lyrical rhythm to the words.<br><br>Since Kanji is often the most intimidating part of being Japanese-literate, getting books with Furigana (tiny phonetic symbols alongside Kanji characters) helps greatly when trying to read Japanese-language Manga. <br><br>Japanese is easiest to disseminate when you know the gist of a said statement. I often read my Love Hina Manga alongside a downloaded english translation. This helps when I find words I don't know, the same as watching subtitled anime.<br><br>Beware of Japanese-English Dictionaries. Books like that are poor at representing a word as said in a sentence, and are practical only as a side aid.<br><br>For your information I'm using the &quot;Teach Yourself Japanese&quot; book, with accompanying audio cassete, in conjunction with the Random House-Webster's Pocket Japanese Dictionary. <br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showPrevMessage?topicID=649.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showNextMessage?topicID=649.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=649.topic&index=6><img src=http://www.polykarbon.com/bbsimage/addreply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.emailToFriend?topicID=649.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.threadControl?topicID=649.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/professional/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands (Moderator only)</a><br> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=649.topic>Subscribe</a> Click to receive email notification of replies<br>  <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=649.topic>Unsubscribe</a> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies<br> </td><td align="right" valign="top"></td></tr><tr align="right"><td colspan=2><form action=http://pub25.ezboard.com/BBSForum.jumpShowForum method=post><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="1"><tr><td><b>jump to:</b><select name=forumName><option value="polykarbonbbsfrm18">PK-BBS Rules and Regulations!<option value="polykarbonbbsfrm27">Board F.A.Q.s<option 